com.infinitydb.map.visitor

Class Visitable<K,V>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.infinitydb.map.visitor.Visitable<K,V>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    VisitableMap<K,V>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    VisitableArrayWrapper, VisitableListWrapper, VisitableMapWrapper, VisitableSetWrapper

    public abstract class Visitable<K,V>
extends java.lang.Object
implements VisitableMap<K,V>
    A Visitable has only one important abstract method - forEach(), and it has various configuration capabilities for use with high-speed MapVisitor s.

    The scan using visitable.forEach(mapVisitor) invokes accept(key, value) on the Visitable zero or more times as for any Map.

    The common idiom (which is similar to a regular Map) is: 

     visitable.forEach(mapVisitor);
    where the MapVisitor may also be subclassed as a ThreadedMapVisitor. If more control of the visitable is desired with setXXX(?) methods: 
     visitableMap.getVisitable().setXXX(?).forEach(mapVisitor);

    Other types of collections can be handled as if they were Maps and abstracted as a set of key/value pairs. For example, see VisitableListWrapper, which abstracts a List as a sequence of indexes as the keys and the list contents at the corresponding indexes as values.

    Another idiom prevents threading even if available. Threaded visiting will normally happen if supported by the Visitable and the MapVisitor extends ThreadedMapVisitor. Threading may bypassed because threading may put additional load on the system that may not be desirable, affecting the latency in some cases by tying up most of the cores. Threading can be turned back on with the setThreadedAllowed(true) on a Visitable. 

     visitableMap.getVisitable().setThreadingAllowed(false).forEach(mapVisitor);
    Also: if the algorithm being used is insensitive to ordering, setReorderingAllowed(true) may be used to indicate that it would be OK for the Visitable to re-order the key parameters to the visit()'s if that will increase performance. The default is false. 
     visitableMap.getVisitable().setReorderingAllowed(true).forEach(mapVisitor);
    A setRemoteAllowed(false) indicates that it is not OK for the Visitable to send instances of the MapVisitor to remote systems such as other local or remote JVMs. If the MapVisitor extends RemoteMapVisitor by default the remoting will occur, but there may be additional load on the system due to network I/O for example. To disallow both threading and remote(), control them independently. This means it is possible to have the remote JVM's execute without threading, and also with or without reordering allowed. 
     visitableMap.getVisitable().setRemoteAllowed(false).forEach(biConsumer);

      • isReorderingAllowed

        public boolean isReorderingAllowed()
        Setting reorderingAllowed true makes it allowable for the Visitable to invoke the visit(key, value) with the keys out of order, usually only for speed. If the Visitable itself is not ordered, such as a hash map, then the keys are not necessarily ordered anyway. Note that some MapVisitor algorithms may require ordering, so setting this true may affect correctness. Defaults false.
        Returns:
        whether reordering is allowed

      • setThreadingThreshold

        public Visitable<K,V> setThreadingThreshold(long threadingThreshold)
        If -1 it means the VisitableMap chooses a default, otherwise it is a suggestion to determine the point of the map size (or wrapped list etc) at which the VisitableMap switches from single-thread execution to multi-thread. The defaults are usually very good and can be dynamically determined by the Map. Ignored in version 3.0 20-6-2016.
        Parameters:
        threadingThreshold - suggested number of Entries below which scanning is serial
        Returns:
        this Visitable for chaining
